docs.abstract: Tensions are mounting over whether Pres Obama can keep campaign pledge to close military prison at Guantanamo Bay Naval Base in Cuba, even as structure decays and inmates age; government is bracing for a wave of new habeas corpus lawsuits after American combat operations in Afghanistan come to an end in December, raising issue of whether legal basis for wartime detentions at Guantanamo Bay has expired.

docs.snippet: Debt scolds hate good fiscal news so much that most Americans haven’t heard that the deficit plunge of the past several years continues.
docs.lead_paragraph: Debt scolds hate good fiscal news so much that most Americans haven’t heard that the deficit plunge of the past several years continues.
docs.abstract: Paul Krugman Op-Ed column examines why there has been so little fanfare surrounding fact that deficit has fallen significantly and continues to fall; blames news media coverage of deficit, which plays up bad news and downplays good news, if it is reported at all; criticizes deficit scolds, who in fact love big budget deficits because fears of fiscal crisis are their best hope of getting big cuts in social programs, which is their ultimate goal.

docs.snippet: The number of Cubans attempting the voyage to the United States has nearly doubled in the past two years, putting the spotlight on the growing frustration with a post-Fidel Cuba.
docs.lead_paragraph: The number of Cubans attempting the voyage to the United States has nearly doubled in the past two years, putting the spotlight on the growing frustration with a post-Fidel Cuba.
docs.abstract: Rising tide of Cubans in rickety, cobbled-together boats is fleeing the island and showing up in the waters of Florida; not since rafter crisis of 1994 has United States received so many Cuban migrants; increase highlights consequences of a US immigration policy that gives preferential treatment to Cubans and on loosened travel restrictions on island, and it shines light on growing frustration of a post-Fidel Castro Cuba.

headline.main: In Rickety Boats, Cuban Migrants Again Flee to U.S.

docs.snippet: Voters appear ready to say to Congress, we hate you for your inaction. Now do more of the same.
docs.lead_paragraph: Voters appear ready to say to Congress, we hate you for your inaction. Now do more of the same.
docs.abstract: Timothy Egan Op-Ed column questions why American voters, majority of whom oppose what Republican Party stands for, appear ready to give them control of Senate and greater hold on House in elections; lists number of risks that greater Republican control of Congress poses and urges voters to consider exactly what Republicans believe; accuses GOP of petty partisanship and, in some cases, crazy thinking.
